SIMPLE: exaggeration
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Exaggeration
<hw>Ex*ag`ger*a"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>exaggeratio</ets> : cf. F. <ets>exag⟦eacute⟧ration</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of heaping or piling up.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Exaggeration</xex> of sand.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Sir M. Hale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of exaggerating; the act of doing or
representing in an excessive manner; a going beyond the bounds of truth
reason, or justice; a hyperbolical representation; hyperbole;
overstatement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No need of an <qex>exaggeration</qex> of what they saw.</q>
<rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <def>A representation of things
beyond natural life, in expression, beauty, power, vigor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Exaggerative</ent>⟦br⟧
